790	chemistry	fluorescent_protein_oligomeric_state	### Background\nMonomeric FPs are ideal tools for fluorescent tagging in biomedical imaging whereas oligomeric FPs hinder their usage as tagging labels because of their tendencies to aggregate. The prediction of oligomeric states is helpful for enhancing live biomedical imaging. Computational prediction of FP oligomeric states can accelerate the effort of protein engineering efforts of creating monomeric FPs. To the best of our knowledge, this study represents the first dataset for predicting and analyzing FP oligomerization directly from the amino acid sequence. Therefore, such data can be used for building classification models for classifying the FPs as being either in the monomeric or oligomeric states.\n\n### About the data set\nInitially, a data set consisting of 409 FPs along with their oligomeric states were compiled from the primary literature. Redundancy reduction of the sequence was performed using the CDâ€“HIT algorithm [19] as implemented in the cdhitHR function of the BioSeqClass R package. Threshold values of 0.95, 0.99 and 1.00 (i.e. corresponding to 95%, 99% and 100%, respectively) was set using the identity argument to produce a reduced subset consisting of 136, 261 and 397 FPs, respectively.\n\nThus, after data curation an exhaustive data set consisting of 397 non-redundant FP oligomeric states was manually compiled from the literature. \n\nThe oligomeric state has 3 classes: 1) monomers, 2) dimers and 3) tetramers.\n\nModels that can be built from the dataset could potentially provide useful insights on the important residues governing the oligomerization of FP. For instance, what patterns are commonly found for the monomer class versus the oligomer class, etc.\n\n### Getting started\n\nInterested users of this dataset can:\n- use the ``AminoAcidSequence`` column to compute amino acid descriptors\n- use the ``OligomericState`` column as the class label. For the purpose of analysis and model building, users can group the ``dimers`` and ``tetramers`` together and rename them to belong to the same group of ``oligomer``.\n\n### Further information\n\nIf you would like further information, please read the full research article describing the use of this data set for predictive model building in the following research article:\n\n&gt; Simeon S, Shoombuatong W, Anuwongcharoen N, Preeyanon L, Prachayasittikul V, Wikberg JES, Nantasenamat C. osFP: a web server for predicting the oligomeric states of fluorescent proteins. Journal of Cheminformatics 8 (2016) 72.\n\nThe original code and data is provided on [GitHub](https://github.com/chaninn/osFP) by the research lab of Associate Professor Chanin Nantasenamat at https://github.com/chaninn/osFP.\n\n### Citing us\n\nIf you use this data set for your own research please cite the following article:\n\n&gt; Simeon S, Shoombuatong W, Anuwongcharoen N, Preeyanon L, Prachayasittikul V, Wikberg JES, Nantasenamat C. [osFP: a web server for predicting the oligomeric states of fluorescent proteins](https://jcheminf.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13321-016-0185-8). Journal of Cheminformatics 8 (2016) 72.	kaggle	kaggle.com/datasets/chaninnantasenamat/fluorescent-protein-oligomeric-state	{"earth and nature",biology,chemistry,biotechnology}	{copyright-authors}	{Name,OligomericState,AminoAcidSequence,Source}	409	4	1636	2	0.9411764705882353
