827	chemistry	Rocky Intertidal Data	## File and Column Descriptions\n\n| File | Columns |\n| --- | --- |\n| Sessile Benthic Invertebrates | Location (m), 4 Animal columns (see table 2), Side |\n| Small Mobile Invertebrates | Location (m), 4 Animal columns, Side |\n| Large Mobile Invertebrates | Location (m), 5 Animal columns, Side |\n| Water Chemistry | Location (m), DO, pH, Temperature (C), Salinity |\n\n- Location: Refers to the distance (in meters) from the transect line with 0 being furthest inland and 45 being closest to the water\n- [Animals]: Count of [Animal] surveyed at that location\n- Side: Side of transect line surveyed for that row (both sides were surveyed separately)\n- DO: Dissolved oxygen (amount of oxygen present in water) measured in tide pool at that location\n- pH: pH (how acidic/basic the water is) measured in tide pool at that location\n- Temperature: Temp (in Â°C) measured in tide pool at that location\n- Salinity: Salinity (dissolved salt in water) measured in tide pool at that location\n\nNote 1: Transect lines are explained in the Methods section.\n\nNote 2: Multiple transect lines were drawn and surveyed for this dataset, so there will be multiple observations for each location/side. This has also caused the appearance of what seem to be duplicate observations. There are no duplicates though, so avoid trying to remove duplicates.\n\n## About the Data\nThe data was collected on November 13th, 2019 by students in the Monday/Wednesday Fall 2019 class of the Marine Biology Laboratory (SIO 136) at Scripps Institute of Oceanography (UCSD). This course is part of the Marine Biology Bachelor of Science program. The instructor for this part of the course was Dovi Kacev (dkacev@ucsd.edu). The person sharing this data (me) was a student in this course.\n\nThe data is a survey of several organisms (see Table 1) in a Rocky Intertidal Zone (see further details about this below). The Rocky Intertidal Zone surveyed was a section of Dike Rock, Scripps Coastal Reserve in La Jolla, CA which â€œis characterized by many large boulders in the high intertidal, broad mud and sandstone benches covered with coralline algal turf in the mid-intertidal, and a mixture of larger boulders and algae-covered flats in the lower intertidal areaâ€ and is a site that has been monitored by LiMPETS since 2007. (1) \n\n*Table 2:* The target species surveyed for each group type\n| Group Type | Target Species |\n| --- | --- |\n| Sessile Benthic Invertebrates | Acorn Barnacles, Goose Neck Barnacles, Sea Anemones, Mussels |\n| Small Mobile Invertebrates | Hermit Crabs, Chitons, Snails, Limpets |\n| Large Mobile Invertebrates | Seahares and Nudibranches, Seastars, Crabs, Cucumbers, Octopus |\n\n## Rocky Intertidal Zone\nThe rocky intertidal zone is an ecosystem found between the low and high tides of rocky beaches. This ecosystem has extreme conditions including desiccation (extreme drying), extreme temperature changes, and being pounded by waves. However, it can also be an optimal place to live for those that can endure the harsh conditions due to having access to a lot of light, nutrients, and oxygen. (2,3) The high intertidal zone is only covered in water during high tide and has species including acorn barnacles, snails, limpets, and shore crabs. The middle intertidal zone is partially covered in water and partially exposed to the air during the day and has species including hermit crabs, chitons, gooseneck barnacles, mussels, aggregating anemones, and some seastars. The low intertidal zone is only exposed during low tides and has species including green anemones, seahares and nudibranchs, cucumbers, and some seastars. Occasionally, octopi will also come into the zone for food. (3-6)\n\nThere are several abiotic and biotic factors at play in the rocky intertidal zone that can affect the ecology of the species living there and each species is affected differently. Abiotic factors are nonliving things that can affect the living organisms such as desiccation. Some organisms can withstand this drying out and so have the ability to live in the higher tidal zones where other organisms would not. However, closer to the shore comes salinity stress and wave action. Biotic factors are living things or processes that affect other organisms such as competition. Competition is one of the biggest biotic factors in the rocky intertidal zone. The abundance of plant material, such as algae and settled juvenile shellfish, can be a biotic factor for small mobile invertebrates because they have to fight with others for the same food source. Small mobile invertebrates also have to deal with predators such as starfish and crabs. (2,3)\n\n## References\n1. https://limpets.org/sites/dike-rock/\n2. http://www.coastalwiki.org/wiki/Rocky_shore_habitat#Desiccation_stress \n3. https://www.nps.gov/rlc/pacificcoast/intertidal-ecosystems.htm\n4. https://www.nps.gov/pore/learn/nature/intertidal.htm \n5. https://biol326.wordpress.com/2018/03/11/lifes-a-beach-challenges-of-living-life-in-the-rocky-intertidal-zone/\n6. https://marinedebris.noaa.gov/sites/default/files/Intertidal%20Zone%20Animals%20Field%20Guide%201.pdf\n7. Photo: https://californiatidepools.com/dike-rock-tide-pools/\n	kaggle	kaggle.com/datasets/ashsummers/rocky-intertidal-data	{"united states",biology,"earth science",animals,environment}	{CC0-1.0}	{Location_m,Nudibranchs,Seastars,Crabs,Cucumbers,Octopuses,Side,Acorn.Barnacles,Goose.Neck.Barnacles,Anemones,Mussels,Hermit.Crabs,Chitons,Snails,Limpets,DO,pH,Temperature_C,Salinty}	450	24	2730	133	0.8235294117647058
